  <bioghist id="aspace_5ab9c9bb21498c74fa47962891eca38b">
    <head>BIOGRAPHICAL NOTE</head>
<p>Schaap was born in New York City on September 27, 1934. He earned a B.S. from Cornell University in 1955 and an M.S. in journalism from Columbia University in 1956. He was sports editor, then general editor, then senior editor for <title>Newsweek</title> from 1956-1963, and in 1964 became city editor of the <title>New York Herald Tribune</title>. He wrote articles for <title>Sports Illustrated</title>, the <title>Saturday Evening Post</title>, and other magazines. His books include <title>Mickey Mantle - Indispensable Yankee</title>; <title>Paul Hornung - Pro Football's Golden Boy</title>; <title>An Illustrated History of the Olympics</title>; <title>Instant Replay</title> (about Jerry Kramer); <title>RFK</title>; and <title>Turned On</title>. He also edited autobiographies of Joe Namath, Frank Beard, and Tom Seaver.</p>  </bioghist>
  <scopecontent id="aspace_2560f955b6a72ffa8640c634d24f0d9e">
    <head>COLLECTION DESCRIPTION</head>
<p>Includes research notes, newspaper clippings, tape recordings and typed transcriptions, drafts of articles and books, and related material from Schaap's career as an author and editor. Also includes material regarding drug addiction, and research material concerning Robert F. Kennedy.</p>  </scopecontent>
